<br>
I have not seen all that much about spell casting mastery though.  Has anyone put points in this?  I would think having specialization kick in more could be a real mana savings thus increasing our damage output over time better.  Well, would like to know what others opionions\first hand knowledge is.<br>
<br>
 <p><center><img src=http://yourpage.blazenet.net/anabelle/triad/valas6.jpg hieght=270 width=216></center><BR>
<center><i>Valas Defai,<a href=http://www.triadcontinuum.com>Triad Continuum</a> </i></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=maruku14>Maruku14</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/31/01 12:58:53 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Spell casting Mastery of Fury</span><hr size=1> I did a little analysis a while back.  Whether Mental Clarity is better or not depends on what your typical day to day scenario is.<br>
<br>
If you're soloing, Mental Clarity is definitely the best choice.  This can be verified rather easily by dividing three by how much mana you regen (going to be 28ish, with BoF and a FT1 item taken into consideration).  This will come out to almost eleven percent.<br>
<br>
Another thing to bear in mind is that the progression of improvement with Spell Casting Fury is not seven-thirds percent at a time; it is, for the record: 0.66, 2.66, 7.0 percent.  With Mental Clarity, at least you'll get about a 3.5 percent boost with each level.  I'm not saying that's a lot.  But it's better than the alternative.<br>
<br>
The last thing you'll want to bear in mind is the consequences of where you spend your archetype points.  Mental Clarity enables Manaburn, which will only be useful for about as long as it takes for Verant to nerf Kunark dragons.  But that's still more use than Spell Casting Fury Mastery, which has been demonstrated to represent the most miserable price/performance of everything a Wizard has the option of buying.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uwhizbangdustyboots.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Whizbang Dustyboots</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<BR>Gnomish Advocate</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/31/01 1:03:11 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Spell casting Mastery of Fury</span><hr size=1> Screw the wizard-only skills. The archetype ones, as a whole, kick ass, with only one being useless for wizards. <p><a href="http://eq.guildmagic.com/character.cfm?ID=49189" target="_blank"><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/whiz/whiz-banner-long-3.gif" height=60 width=468 alt="Whizbang Dustyboots" border=0></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/umikar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mikar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/31/01 4:59:38 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Spell casting Mastery of Fury</span><hr size=1> Maruku <br>
<br>
The question was Mastery (the arch skill) vs Fury - the MC vs Fury debate is already well laid out <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Veladorn<br>
<br>
I think the main problem with Mastery is that its outright hard to test the effect of specialization without access to mana numerically. I have tried - below is a repost of my observations. <br>
<br>
The main problem is that using standing mana regen takes forever to get a decent sized sample - and even then the results have a margin of error thats large compared to any conceivable spec result. So, unless SEQ does indeed provide mana numerically extracted from the data stream and someone with SEQ is willing to run a few tests and posts the results I dont see how we can realistically expect to find out what Mastery does - if anything.<br>
<br>
Observations:<br>
<br>
As a base I logged on my level 16 magician with no specialization yet. Standing with no buffs I cast a 160 mana cost spell the very tick it was possible and then counted number of ticks before I could cast it again. Expected result 160 ticks. Did this 3 times and got 157, 158 and 159 ticks. A small sample I admit but it gives an indication of the margin of error.<br>
<br>
I then logged Mikar on and cast a 100 mana cost spell in my main spec with 2 mana/tick due to MC1. Results from 10 tries were half 44 and half 45 ticks. I have also done a few other tries with higher cost spells and gotten the same 10-12% decrease in mana cost. Not once have I gotten something else though.<br>
<br>
Finally, I just cast a 150 mana non main spec spell twice (before patch cut me short) with 3 mana per tick due to MC2. Results were 48 and 49 ticks.<br>
